Tracking Variables

Suppose we have a variable rate of exposure, and we want to formulate models in which recent exposure affects the epidemiology of disease. We construct the following two time series tracking exposure:

Base PIT Variables: Exposure Tracking

In a population stratified by age, cumulative exposure will vary by age. Let \(V_{a,t}\) denote an immune tracking variable that tracks exposure for people of age \(a\) at time \(t\). It is updated by the following recursive relationship:

\[\begin{equation} V_{a,t+1} = \sigma \alpha_t + (1-\mu) V_{a,t} \end{equation}\]

Note that for \(\mu=0\) and \(\sigma=1\), the equation simply tracks cumulative exposure. This version returns only the last value:

basePIT.0 = function(alpha, mu=0, sigma = 1, vecV = matrix(0,1,1), calO=matrix(1,1,1), N=1, w=1){
  ###################################################################
  # If alpha is a vector (a time series), then N is its length.
  # If alpha is a scalar, then N is passed as an optional argument.
  # Default values update one time step for alpha and mu.
  ###################################################################
  if(length(alpha)==1){
    alpha = rep(alpha, N)
  } else {
    N = length(alpha) 
  }
  # Setting sigma=0 "normalizes" the exposure to mu
  if(sigma==0){
    if(mu==0) print("WARNING: mu=sigma=0.")
    sigma = ifelse(mu==0, 1, mu) 
  } 
  ####################################
  # alpha is the "attack" rate
  # mu describes the "decay"
  # w describes biting weights by age
  # calO is an age operator
  ####################################
  for(t in 1:N){
    vecV = ((1-mu)*vecV + w*sigma*alpha[t])%*%calO
  } 
  return(vecV)
}

This version returns the whole time series (including the initial value):

basePIT.TS = function(alpha, mu=0, sigma = 1, vecV = matrix(0,1,1), calO=matrix(1,1,1), N=1, w=1){
  ###################################################################
  # If alpha is a vector (a time series), then N is its length.
  # If alpha is a scalar, then N is passed as an optional argument.
  # Default values update one time step for alpha and mu.
  ###################################################################
  if(length(alpha)==1){
    alpha = rep(alpha, N)
  } else {
    N = length(alpha) 
  }
  # Setting sigma=0 "normalizes" the exposure to mu
  if(sigma==0){
    if(mu==0) print("WARNING: mu=sigma=0.")
    sigma = ifelse(mu==0, 1, mu) 
  }
  ####################################
  # alpha is the "attack" rate
  # mu describes the "decay"
  # w describes biting weights by age
  # calO is an age operator
  ####################################
  matV = vecV
  for(t in 1:N){
    vecV = ((1-mu)*vecV + w*sigma*alpha[t])%*%calO
    matV = cbind(matV, vecV)
  } 
  return(matV)
}

We write a function plotPITxAge that plots PIT variables by age.

plotPITxAge = function(ages, vecV, lines=FALSE, clr=NULL, d2y=F){
  clr <- ifelse(is.null(clr),"black", clr)
  if(d2y == TRUE) ages <- ages/365
  if(lines==FALSE){
    plot(ages, vecV, type = "l", xlab = "Age (Years)", ylab = "PIT", col = clr)
  } else { 
    lines(ages, vecV, col = clr)
  }
}

We use the age operator, \({\cal O}\) and the 1066 age structure (from the AgeOperators.R in the the Tensor-Model-Library). The following plots cumulative exposure by age. The age structure here tracks populations for 85 years. Black shows 85 years of exposure. Blue shows the results for 10,000 days (~27.4 years) and red for 1,000 days (~2.7 years). Starting from no exposure, we see the relationship saturate. This is a cautionary tale to take care to set the initial conditions for tracking variables \(V_0\) with great care.

source ("../Tensor-Model-Library/AgeOperators.R")
## Loading required package: Matrix
calO = calO_1066()
ages = ages_1066()
vecV = matrix(0,1,66)

plotPITxAge(ages, basePIT.0(0.1, mu=0, sigma=1, vecV, calO, N=3000))
plotPITxAge(ages, basePIT.0(0.1, mu=0, sigma=1, vecV, calO, N=1000), T, "blue")
plotPITxAge(ages, basePIT.0(0.1, mu=0, sigma=1, vecV, calO, N=100), T,"red")

We plot another function, plotPITxTime that plots PIT variables over time.

plotPITxTime = function(tm, vecV, lines=FALSE, clr=NULL, d2y=F){
  clr <- ifelse(is.null(clr),"black", clr)
  if(d2y == TRUE) tm <- tm/365
  if(lines==FALSE){
    plot(tm, vecV, type = "l", xlab = "Time (Years)", ylab = "PIT", col = clr)
  } else { 
    lines(tm, vecV, col = clr)
  }
}

Note that passing \(\sigma=0\) automatically “normalizes” the variables (setting \(\sigma=\mu\)), so that they have the same range:

vecV0 = 0
plot(ttTT[-401], alphaT, col = "red", xlab = "Time (Years)", ylab = "PIT", type="l")
plotPITxTime(ttTT, basePIT.TS(alphaT, mu=0.05, sigma=0, vecV0), T, "black")
plotPITxTime(ttTT, basePIT.TS(alphaT, mu=0.1, sigma=0, vecV0), T, "blue")

plotPITxTime(ttTT, basePIT.TS(alphaT, mu=0.3, sigma=0, vecV0), T,"darkgreen")
plotPITxTime(ttTT, basePIT.TS(alphaT, mu=0.5, sigma=0, vecV0), T,"purple")

Differences in the average value of \(\alpha\) are still reflected in the time series that result:

## Logistic PIT Variables

Next, we use the logistic map, and we add a scaling parameter: \[\begin{equation} V_{a,t+1} = \left( \sigma \alpha_t + (1-\mu) V_{a,t} \right)\left(1-V_{a,t}) \end{equation}\]

logisticPIT.0 = function(alpha, mu=0, sigma=1, vecV = matrix(0,1,1), calO=matrix(1,1,1), N=1, w=1){
  ###################################################################
  # If alpha is a vector (a time series), then N is its length.
  # If alpha is a scalar, then N is passed as an optional argument.
  # Default values update one time step for alpha and mu.
  ###################################################################
  if(length(alpha)==1){
    alpha = rep(alpha, N)
  } else {
    N = length(alpha) 
  }
  # Setting sigma=0 "normalizes" the exposure to mu
  if(sigma==0){
    if(mu==0) print("WARNING: mu=sigma=0.")
    sigma = ifelse(mu==0, 1, mu) 
  } 
  ####################################
  # alpha is the "attack" rate
  # mu describes the "decay"
  # w describes biting weights by age
  # calO is an age operator
  ####################################
  for(t in 1:N){
    vecV = ((1-mu)*vecV + sigma*w*alpha[t])*(1-vecV)%*%calO
  } 
  return(vecV)
}

This version returns the whole time series (including the initial value):

    matV = cbind(matV, vecV)
  } 
  return(matV)
}

Age Scaling

fa = function(a, k1=20, min = 0.0001){
  1 / (exp(-k1/10/5) + exp(-k1*(a-12)/10)) + min 
}
plot(ages, fa(ages), type = "l")
